{"title_page": "Antoine Joly", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Antoine Joly\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1955|07|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = Le Mans\n| ambassador_from = French\n| predecessor   = M. Michel Prom\n| country       = Suriname\n| term_start    = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| ambassador_from2 = French Guinese\n| country2      = CARICOM\n| term_start2   = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = French\n| party         = [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]\n| other_names   = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Antoine Joly''' (Le Mans, [[16 July]] [[1955]]) is a French politician and ambassador. \n\n==Biography==\nJoly graduated from [[Sciences Po]]. He started his career for the City of [[Paris]] and in 1981 became the head of the Tax and Economic Office.<ref name=\"ouest\"/> From 28 March 1993 until 21 April 1997,<ref name=\"assemblee_nationale\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/histoire/trombinoscope/Vrepublique/Legis10/joly-antoine-16071955.asp|title=National Assembly Joly Antoine|access-date=7 April 2020|language=fr|website=Assembl\u00e9e Nationale}}</ref> Joly was the deputy for [[Sarthe's 3rd constituency]] in the National Assembly. His party affiliation is [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]. From 15 July 2011 until August 2015 he served as French ambassador to [[Nicaragua]].\n\nOn 17 January 2017 Joly was appointed as the French ambassador to [[Suriname]] as well the ambassador for French Guiana to the [[CARICOM]].<ref name=\"appointment\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000033888850|title=Decree 16 January 2017|language=fr|access-date=6 April 2020|website=[[Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]] }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Joly became the 8th victim of [[COVID-19]] in [[Suriname]].<ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital|language=nl|access-date=6 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> Joly got infected when he was in a small waiting room of [[Zorg en Hoop Airport]] together with a Dutch person who was later diagnosed positive in [[the Netherlands]].<ref name=\"interview_dwt\">{{Cite news|url=http://dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/04/21/st-laurent-afgesloten-van-rest-frans-guyana/|title=St. Laurent afgesloten van rest Frans-Guyana|website=De Ware Tijd|language=nl|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\nJoly was first treated at the Wanica Hospital in [[Lelydorp]]. Joly only had mild symptoms<ref name=\"interview_dwt\"/>, therefore he was transported to Cayenne in French Guiana on 29 March 2020, where he was quarantined.<ref name=\"ouest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/coronavirus-originaire-de-la-sarthe-l-ambassadeur-de-france-au-suriname-contamine-6795268|title=Original from Sarthe, the French ambassador to Suriname has been infected|language=fr|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Ouest France}}</ref> On 7 April 2020 Joly recovered from Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8oPhY-Kg81g|title=French ambassador to Suriname about the situation in Suriname, Joly Antoine - Guyana (youtube)|language=fr|website=[[La Premi\u00e8re (France)|Guyane la 1\u00e8re]] via youtube|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> On 8 April 2020, Joly returned to Suriname to resume his duties. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid-19.sr/reeds-vier-covid-19-patienten-genezen-verklaard-geen-nieuwe-gevallen/|title=4 Covid 19 patients cured. No new cases|language=nl|access-date=9 April 2020|website=Covid Suriname}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{#related:South America}}\n{{#related:French Guiana}}\n{{#related:Nicaragua}}\n{{#related:Netherlands}}\n{{#related:Suriname}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joly, Antoine}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Antoine Joly\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1955|07|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = Le Mans\n| ambassador_from = French\n| predecessor   = M. Michel Prom\n| country       = Suriname\n| term_start    = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| ambassador_from2 = French Guinese\n| country2      = CARICOM\n| term_start2   = 17 January 2017 <ref name=\"appointment\" />\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = French\n| party         = [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]\n| other_names   = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Antoine Joly''' (Le Mans, [[16 July]] [[1955]]) is a French politician and ambassador. \n\n==Biography==\nJoly graduated from [[Sciences Po]]. He started his career for the City of [[Paris]] and in 1981 became the head of the Tax and Economic Office.<ref name=\"ouest\"/> From 28 March 1993 until 21 April 1997,<ref name=\"assemblee_nationale\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/histoire/trombinoscope/Vrepublique/Legis10/joly-antoine-16071955.asp|title=National Assembly Joly Antoine|access-date=7 April 2020|language=fr|website=Assembl\u00e9e Nationale}}</ref> Joly was the deputy for [[Sarthe's 3rd constituency]] in the National Assembly. His party affiliation is [[Rally for the Republic|RPR]]. From 15 July 2011 until August 2015 he served as French ambassador to [[Nicaragua]].\n\nOn 17 January 2017 Joly was appointed as the French ambassador to [[Suriname]] as well the ambassador for French Guiana to the [[CARICOM]].<ref name=\"appointment\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000033888850|title=Decree 16 January 2017|language=fr|access-date=6 April 2020|website=[[Journal Officiel de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]] }}\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Joly became the 8th victim of [[COVID-19]] in [[Suriname]].<ref name=\"antoine_joly\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/03/25/franse-ambassadeur-in-isolatie-in-wanica-ziekenhuis/|title=French Ambassador in isolation in Wanica Hospital|language=nl|access-date=6 April 2020|website=De Ware Tijd}}</ref> Joly got infected when he was in a small waiting room of [[Zorg en Hoop Airport]] together with a Dutch person who was later diagnosed positive in [[the Netherlands]].<ref name=\"interview_dwt\">{{Cite news|url=http://dwtonline.com/laatste-nieuws/2020/04/21/st-laurent-afgesloten-van-rest-frans-guyana/|title=St. Laurent afgesloten van rest Frans-Guyana|website=De Ware Tijd|language=nl|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\nJoly was first treated at the Wanica Hospital in [[Lelydorp]]. Joly only had mild symptoms<ref name=\"interview_dwt\"/>, therefore he was transported to Cayenne in French Guiana on 29 March 2020, where he was quarantined.<ref name=\"ouest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sante/virus/coronavirus/coronavirus-originaire-de-la-sarthe-l-ambassadeur-de-france-au-suriname-contamine-6795268|title=Original from Sarthe, the French ambassador to Suriname has been infected|language=fr|access-date=6 April 2020|website=Ouest France}}</ref> On 7 April 2020 Joly recovered from Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8oPhY-Kg81g|title=French ambassador to Suriname about the situation in Suriname, Joly Antoine - Guyana (youtube)|language=fr|website=[[La Premi\u00e8re (France)|Guyane la 1\u00e8re]] via youtube|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> On 8 April 2020, Joly returned to Suriname to resume his duties. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid-19.sr/reeds-vier-covid-19-patienten-genezen-verklaard-geen-nieuwe-gevallen/|title=4 Covid 19 patients cured. No new cases|language=nl|access-date=9 April 2020|website=Covid Suriname}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{#related:South America}}\n{{#related:French Guiana}}\n{{#related:Nicaragua}}\n{{#related:Netherlands}}\n{{#related:Suriname}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joly, Antoine}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoine_Joly"}
{"title_page": "St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn)", "text_new": "__NOTOC__{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =St. Paul's Episcopal Church Carroll Street\n| nrhp_type =\n| image = St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn.jpg\n| image_size = 325px\n| caption = (2013)\n| location= 199 Carroll Street<br />[[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|40|55|N|73|58|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City#New York#USA\n| built =1867-1884<ref name=aia>{{cite aia5|page=626}}</ref>\n| architect= [[Richard Upjohn & Son]; Richard M. Upjohn]<br />[[Ralph Adams Cram]]\n| architecture= [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic]]<ref name=aia />\n| added = December 21, 1989\n| governing_body = Vestry\n| refnum=89002086<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn''' at 199 Carroll Street in the [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]] was built from 1867 to 1884 and was designed by [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<ref name=aia /> in the [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic style]].  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1989.<ref name=nris/>\n\nThe parish is part of the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]] in the [[Episcopal Diocese of Long Island]], part of the worldwide [[Anglican Communion]], in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition.\n\n== Parish history ==\nSt. Paul's was founded on Christmas Day of 1849, in [[South Brooklyn]], then the quickly developing southward expansion of old [[Brooklyn Heights]]. New homes and businesses were covering old countryside, farmland, and shoreline; [[industrialization]] was bringing a new way of life to the [[City of Brooklyn]], waves of immigrants from the nations of the world were arriving and the [[American Civil War]] was looming.  This was also the era when the [[Anglican Communion]] of Churches was experiencing a renewed vision of their catholic faith and order often called the \"Anglo-Catholic Revival\" of the [[Oxford Movement]]. Saint Paul's was formed in heady days of philosophical, social, economic, and religious change.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3330|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:St. Paul's Protestant Episcopal Church|date=October 1989|accessdate=2011-02-20 |author=Kathleen LaFrank|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3331|title=Accompanying six photos}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|Christianity}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn, New York)}}\n*[http://www.stpaulscarrollst.org/ Official website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pauls Church, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:Properties of religious function on the National Register of Historic Places in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1866]]\n[[Category:19th-century Episcopal church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Episcopal church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Culture of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Richard Michell Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Richard Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{Brooklyn-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Brooklyn-church-stub}}\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__{{Infobox NRHP \n| name =St. Paul's Episcopal Church\n| nrhp_type =\n| image = St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn.jpg\n| image_size = 325px\n| caption = (2013)\n| location= 423 Clinton Street<br />[[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|40|55|N|73|58|25|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = New York City#New York#USA\n| built =1867-1884<ref name=aia>{{cite aia5|page=626}}</ref>\n| architect= [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<br />[[Ralph Adams Cram]]\n| architecture= [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic]]<ref name=aia />\n| added = December 21, 1989\n| governing_body = Private\n| refnum=89002086<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''St. Paul's Episcopal Church of Brooklyn''' at 423 Clinton Street at Carroll Street in the [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]] was built from 1867 to 1884 and was designed by [[Richard Upjohn & Son]]<ref name=aia /> in the [[Gothic revival architecture|High Victorian Gothic style]].  It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1989.<ref name=nris/>\n\nThe parish is part of the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]] in the [[Episcopal Diocese of Long Island]], part of the worldwide [[Anglican Communion]], in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition.\n\n== Parish history ==\nSt. Paul's was founded on Christmas Day of 1849, in [[South Brooklyn]], then the quickly developing southward expansion of old [[Brooklyn Heights]]. New homes and businesses were covering old countryside, farmland, and shoreline; [[industrialization]] was bringing a new way of life to the [[City of Brooklyn]], waves of immigrants from the nations of the world were arriving and the [[American Civil War]] was looming.  This was also the era when the [[Anglican Communion]] of Churches was experiencing a renewed vision of their catholic faith and order often called the \"Anglo-Catholic Revival\" of the [[Oxford Movement]]. Saint Paul's was formed in heady days of philosophical, social, economic, and religious change.<ref name=\"nrhpinv_ny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3330|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration:St. Paul's Protestant Episcopal Church|date=October 1989|accessdate=2011-02-20 |author=Kathleen LaFrank|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]}} ''See also:'' {{cite web|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=3331|title=Accompanying six photos}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|Christianity}}\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline|St. Paul's Episcopal Church (Brooklyn, New York)}}\n*[http://www.stpaulscarrollst.org/ Official website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Pauls Church, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:Properties of religious function on the National Register of Historic Places in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gothic Revival church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1866]]\n[[Category:19th-century Episcopal church buildings]]\n[[Category:Churches in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Catholic church buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Episcopal church buildings in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Culture of Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Richard Michell Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Richard Upjohn church buildings]]\n[[Category:Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1866 establishments in New York (state)]]\n\n\n{{Brooklyn-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Brooklyn-church-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wlogburn", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Paul%27s_Episcopal_Church_(Brooklyn)"}
